<subsection xml:id="subsec-the-cartesian-plane">
    <title>the cartesian plane</title>

    <p>
        Coordinates refer to an ordered pair of numbers (x, y), that represent the exact location of a point on the Cartesian plane.
    </p>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The x-coordinate tells you how far left or right the point is from the origin.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The y-coordinate tells you how far up or down the point is from the origin.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <activity>
        <p>
            <m>{\color{red} \textbf{Work in groups}}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Draw Two Perpendicular Lines
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Use a ruler to draw a horizontal line (x-axis).
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Draw a vertical line (y-axis) that intersects the x-axis at a right angle.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Label the intersection point as (0,0), called the origin.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Label the Axes
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Write “x-axis” below the horizontal line.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Write “y-axis” beside the vertical line.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Mark Equal Intervals
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Choose a scale (e.g., 1, 2, 5, or 10).
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Mark and label positive numbers to the right on the x-axis and above on the y-axis.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Mark and label negative numbers to the left on the x-axis and below on the y-axis.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Check
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Ensure the numbers are evenly spaced.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Make sure the x-axis and y-axis are clearly labeled.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Discuss and compare your diagrams
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
        <m>{\color{green} \textbf{Learning Point}}</m>
    </p>
    <image>
        <latex-image label="h">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                \draw[very thin,gray!50] (-4,-4) grid (4,4);
    
                % Draw x and y axes
                \draw[thick,->] (-4.5,0) -- (4.5,0) node[anchor=north] {\textbf{x}};
                \draw[thick,->] (0,-4.5) -- (0,4.5) node[anchor=east] {\textbf{y}};
                
                % Grid and labels
                \foreach \x in {-4,-3,-2,-1,1,2,3,4} {
                    \draw[thick] (\x,-0.1) -- (\x,0.1); % Tick marks on x-axis
                    \node[anchor=north] at (\x,-0.2) {\textbf{\x}};
                }

                \foreach \y in {-4,-3,-2,-1,1,2,3,4} {
                    \draw[thick] (-0.1,\y) -- (0.1,\y); % Tick marks on y-axis
                    \node[anchor=east] at (-0.2,\y) {\textbf{\y}};
                }

                % Origin
                \node[anchor=north east] at (-0.1,-0.1) {\textbf{0}};
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
        
    </image>
    <p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    X-Axis is the horizontal number line in the Cartesian plane.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Y-Axis is the vertical number line in the Cartesian plane.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
</subsection>